title: Police appeal for key witness after woman hit by train | Central
text:
Police are appealing for a key witness to come forward after a woman was killed by a train.
The 29-year-old woman, from Dublin, was confirmed dead at the scene after the incident at Barnt Green station just before 7am on Thursday.
Her death is not being treated as suspicious.
Witness reports suggested the woman and a man had been trying to cross the railway tracks to change platforms. The man was unhurt.
Police said the woman had arrived on a ferry from Ireland into Holyhead early on Thursday before taking a coach to Birmingham.
The woman's death is not being treated as suspicious Credit: BPM She was then spotted on CCTV at New Street Station with a man at around 5.30am.
The duo were understood to have been heading for Worcester and boarded a service to Redditch shortly before 6am.
They then got off at Barnt Green and tried to walk across the line when the woman was struck by a service heading from Worcester to New Street.
British Transport Police have since uncovered a CCTV image from New Street station of a man they wish to speak to concerning the incident.
Police are trying to trace this man in connection with the incident Credit: BPM Detective Chief Inspector Tony Fitzpatrick said:
I would like to stress he is not in any trouble – we just need to talk to him.
The woman’s family are understandably devastated and it is important we understand the circumstances leading up to her death so we can give them the answers they so desperately need.
– Detective Chief Inspector Tony Fitzpatrick The incident saw significant disruption to the Cross City rail line until around 10.30am on Thursday morning.
